04743nam a22004575i 9781503615731DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20221996cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815036157317 a10.1515/97815036157312doi  a(DE-B1597)582253  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aHIS0290002bisacsh1 aSeaver, Kirsten A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Frozen Echo :bGreenland and the Exploration of North American, ca. A.D. 1000-1500 /cKirsten A. Seaver. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©1996  a1 online resource (408 p.) :billus  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER ONE Greenland and Vínland: North Atlantic Exploration Five Hundred Years Before the Cabot Voyages -- tCHAPTER TWO Social and Economic Conditions in Norse Greenland Before 1350 -- tCHAPTER THREE Church and Trade in Norse Greenland Before 1350 -- tCHAPTER FOUR Ivar Bárdarson's Greenland -- tCHAPTER FIVE The Western Settlement Comes to an End -- tCHAPTER SIX Rumors of Trouble in the Eastern Settlement -- tCHAPTER SEVEN England and the Norwegian Colonies, I400-I450 -- tCHAPTER EIGHT Sailing out of the Middle Ages, 1450-1500 -- tCHAPTER NINE Greenland, 1450-1500 -- tCHAPTER TEN The Age of Discovery -- tAPPENDIX A The Lawman Thorstein Eyjolfsson and His Descendants -- tAPPENDIX B Sigrid Björnsdaughter -- tAPPENDIX C Overlapping Enterprises, ca. 1480-1510 -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt is now generally accepted the Leif Eriksson sailed from Greenland across the Davis Strait and made landfalls on the North American continent almost a thousand years ago, but what happened in this vast area during the next five hundred years has long been a source of disagreement among scholars. Using new archeological, scientific, and documentary information (much of it in Scandinavian languages that are a bar to most Western historians), this book confronts many of the unanswered questions about early exploration and colonization along the shores of the Davis Strait. The author brings together two distinct but tangential fields of inquiry: the history of medieval Greenland and its connections with the Norse discovery of North America, and fifteenth-century British maritime history and pre-colonial voyages to North America, including that of John Cabot. In order to evaluate the situation in Norse Greenland at the end of the fifteenth century (when documented English and Portuguese voyages of northern exploration began), the author follows the colony's development—its domestic economy and foreign trade and its cultural and ecclesiastical affinities—from its inception in the tenth century. In the process, she looks critically at commonly held views that have gone unchallenged until now. Among the questions about which the author sets forth new evidence and conclusions are: the extent to which Greenlanders explored and exploited North America after Leif Eriksson, the reasons for the baffling disappearance of the Norse settlement in Greenland, the connection between their disappearance and the beginning of the voyages of exploration that began around A.D. 1500, the routes by which information concerning previous voyages traveled, the history before Cabot of the advance of English fishing fleets from Icelandic waters to the coasts of Labrador, and the influence of the roman Catholic Church on Norse Greenland.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 4aHistory -- World. 7aHISTORY / North America.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-200